WEBVTT

00:00.626 --> 00:02.456
I have yet to give him
my answer.

00:03.253 --> 00:05.423
I’ll no’ stand in the way
of yer happiness.

00:05.506 --> 00:06.506
[ dramatic music ]

00:06.590 --> 00:08.300
Ye will escort Claire home.

00:08.383 --> 00:09.383
What about the militia?

00:09.510 --> 00:11.340
I made ye a captain
without time

00:11.470 --> 00:12.850
to teach ye
what the word meant.

00:12.930 --> 00:14.760
Da left you here to protect
the Ridge while he’s gone.

00:14.848 --> 00:16.518
He doesn’t respect me, Bree.

00:16.600 --> 00:18.440
I’ve told Gerald Forbes

00:18.519 --> 00:19.689
to draw up a will,
leaving River Run

00:19.811 --> 00:22.481
and all its contents
to Jeremiah.

00:22.564 --> 00:24.614
Mistress Fraser,
I’d like to introduce you

00:24.691 --> 00:26.111
to Mr. Wylie.

00:26.193 --> 00:27.533
♪

00:27.611 --> 00:29.361
‐ JAMIE: Who’s Dr. Rawlings?
‐ Me.

00:30.322 --> 00:32.122
It’s no longer safe
for you to remain here.

00:32.199 --> 00:33.699
I know you stay
because of the vow

00:33.784 --> 00:36.584
you made to my mother
and to me.

00:36.703 --> 00:39.373
I release you from it.
Be hard to find.

00:39.498 --> 00:42.708
♪

00:43.168 --> 00:45.548
CHOIR:
♪ Sing me a song ♪

00:45.671 --> 00:48.551
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

00:48.674 --> 00:50.684
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

00:50.759 --> 00:54.139
♪ Be I? ♪

00:54.221 --> 00:56.261
♪ Merry of soul ♪

00:56.390 --> 00:59.270
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

00:59.393 --> 01:01.353
♪ Over the sea ♪

01:01.436 --> 01:04.606
♪ To Skye ♪

01:04.731 --> 01:07.281
♪ Billow and breeze ♪

01:07.401 --> 01:09.781
♪ Islands and seas ♪

01:09.903 --> 01:12.573
♪ Mountains of rain and sun ♪

01:12.698 --> 01:14.948
♪ Mountains of rain
and sun ♪

01:15.075 --> 01:17.575
♪ All that was good ♪

01:17.661 --> 01:20.251
♪ All that was fair ♪

01:20.330 --> 01:22.500
♪ All that was me ♪

01:22.583 --> 01:25.423
♪ Is gone ♪

01:25.544 --> 01:27.594
♪ Sing me a song ♪

01:27.713 --> 01:30.553
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

01:30.632 --> 01:32.472
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

01:32.593 --> 01:35.723
♪ Be I? ♪

01:35.804 --> 01:37.854
♪ Merry of soul ♪

01:37.931 --> 01:41.141
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

01:41.268 --> 01:45.438
♪ Over the sea ♪

01:45.564 --> 01:51.444
♪ To Skye ♪

01:51.570 --> 01:54.410
[ dramatic music ]

01:54.489 --> 01:56.909
♪

01:56.992 --> 02:01.372
WOMAN:
♪ Sing me a song ♪

02:01.455 --> 02:06.635
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

02:06.710 --> 02:11.460
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

02:11.548 --> 02:13.298
♪ Be I? ♪

02:13.383 --> 02:16.343
♪

02:16.470 --> 02:19.310
[ tense music ]

02:19.389 --> 02:22.309
♪

02:41.078 --> 02:42.498
There are dragoons ahead.

02:44.414 --> 02:45.504
Halt.

02:45.624 --> 02:46.834
[ horse whinnies ]

02:57.969 --> 02:59.299
Make yourselves known.

03:02.557 --> 03:04.307
Thank goodness.

03:04.393 --> 03:06.443
Oh, you are a welcome sight,
Lieutenant.

03:08.689 --> 03:11.399
We are making our way
as far as possible
from Culloden.

03:11.525 --> 03:13.695
Whom do I address, sir?

03:13.777 --> 03:14.897
Of course,
where are my manners?

03:15.028 --> 03:17.488
Uh, I am Samuel Torrington.

03:17.572 --> 03:20.532
My wife and daughter
are inside.

03:20.617 --> 03:21.867
Will you have them step out?

03:21.993 --> 03:24.043
By order
of the duke of Cumberland,

03:24.121 --> 03:26.081
we are to search every
conveyance on these roads.

03:27.541 --> 03:28.711
Very wise precaution.

03:28.792 --> 03:31.252
[ suspenseful music ]

03:31.378 --> 03:33.128
My dears.

03:33.213 --> 03:35.173
♪

03:35.257 --> 03:36.507
Not a word.

03:36.591 --> 03:39.511
♪

03:58.697 --> 04:01.407
[ objects rustling ]

04:04.745 --> 04:06.165
It’s empty, sir.

04:06.830 --> 04:09.210
Very well.
You should be on your way.

04:16.089 --> 04:17.379
Allow me, miss.

04:17.466 --> 04:18.926
LIEUTENANT:
Have you a destination, sir?

04:20.093 --> 04:22.933
To the border,
across to Carlisle.

04:23.013 --> 04:24.683
My brother has an estate.

04:24.765 --> 04:26.435
LIEUTENANT:
You’ll be far
from the fighting there.

04:28.143 --> 04:30.773
Good day, sir.
Travel safely.

04:30.896 --> 04:32.766
HECTOR:
Thank you.
God save the king.

04:32.856 --> 04:35.606
[ ominous music ]

04:35.734 --> 04:38.784
♪

04:38.904 --> 04:40.284
And which king would that be?

04:41.948 --> 04:43.908
Lieutenant, gold...

04:43.992 --> 04:45.242
with the king of France’s
mark on it.

04:47.120 --> 04:48.580
Must be intended
for Charles Stuart.

04:49.623 --> 04:51.793
We’ve found ourselves
some Jacobite traitors.

04:51.917 --> 04:53.207
Hector.

04:53.293 --> 04:55.753
♪

04:55.837 --> 04:57.167
[ guns cocking ]

04:57.297 --> 04:58.507
Sir, lower your weapon.

04:58.632 --> 04:59.632
[ gunshot ]

04:59.758 --> 05:01.178
[ horses whinny ]

05:01.301 --> 05:02.591
‐ Papa!
‐ [ gunshot ]

05:04.054 --> 05:05.564
[ shrieks ]

05:06.765 --> 05:09.645
[ screams, panting ]

05:09.726 --> 05:11.096
Morna?

05:13.396 --> 05:15.516
[ moaning ]

05:15.649 --> 05:18.399
♪

05:19.611 --> 05:21.361
Morna. Morna.

05:21.488 --> 05:23.528
‐ [ body thuds ]
‐ JOCASTA: Morna.

05:23.657 --> 05:25.027
Morna.
[ sniffles ]

05:27.327 --> 05:28.657
Morna?

05:28.745 --> 05:30.195
[ speaking Gaelic ]

05:30.330 --> 05:32.290
‐ She’s dead.
‐ No.

05:32.374 --> 05:34.924
‐ Ye canna help her.
‐ No, no.

05:35.001 --> 05:37.921
[ solemn music ]

05:38.004 --> 05:39.424
We must go.

05:39.506 --> 05:40.466
No.

05:40.549 --> 05:42.049
[ whimpers ]

05:42.175 --> 05:43.925
‐ HECTOR: Jocasta, come.
‐ Hector, we canna leave her.

05:44.010 --> 05:45.720
[ sobs ]

05:45.846 --> 05:47.006
Morna!

05:47.138 --> 05:48.808
[ tense music ]

05:48.890 --> 05:50.430
[ Jocasta sobs ]

05:50.517 --> 05:53.437
♪

05:53.520 --> 05:54.770
Drive on!

05:54.855 --> 05:56.025
Ya!

05:57.482 --> 05:58.982
♪

05:59.067 --> 06:00.527
Morna!
Morna!

06:00.652 --> 06:03.532
♪

06:03.655 --> 06:04.865
Morna!

06:04.948 --> 06:07.828
[ sobbing ]

06:07.909 --> 06:11.039
♪

06:16.042 --> 06:17.342
[ knock at door ]

06:17.419 --> 06:18.959
DUNCAN:
Do ye have a moment, ma’am?

06:19.045 --> 06:20.245
Come in.

06:23.300 --> 06:25.010
Good morning, Mr. Innes.

06:25.093 --> 06:27.183
Uh, sorry to disturb ye.

06:27.262 --> 06:30.562
Margaret, Abigail,
ye may leave us.

06:35.437 --> 06:37.687
I ken the wedding’s tomorrow,
but, um...

06:37.772 --> 06:38.732
[ door clicks shut ]

06:38.857 --> 06:40.357
I wanted to give ye this.

06:42.235 --> 06:44.065
Is that lavender I smell?

06:44.154 --> 06:46.414
Aye, to soothe yer nerves,
perhaps.

06:48.074 --> 06:50.414
I ken a bride has
much on her mind...

06:50.535 --> 06:53.655
flowers and frocks
and ribbons to choose.

06:57.417 --> 06:59.537
It’s the MacKenzie motto.

07:00.795 --> 07:03.165
"I shine, not burn."

07:03.256 --> 07:06.336
A wee token of my affection.

07:10.889 --> 07:12.099
[ sighs ]

07:12.223 --> 07:14.483
I ken perhaps that...

07:15.477 --> 07:18.097
Ye dinna burn with passion
for me, but...

07:20.941 --> 07:24.781
The name Innes comes
from the Gaelic:

07:24.861 --> 07:26.701
an island formed

07:26.780 --> 07:29.950
by two branches of a stream,

07:30.033 --> 07:33.123
and in time...

07:33.244 --> 07:34.624
I hope that we might‐‐

07:34.746 --> 07:36.406
Thank ye.

07:36.498 --> 07:38.498
Thank ye...
[ chuckles ]
Mr. Innes.

07:38.625 --> 07:40.295
It is most kind.

07:40.377 --> 07:41.497
[ door clicks open ]

07:41.628 --> 07:43.378
ULYSSES:
Pardon me, Mistress.

07:43.463 --> 07:44.383
Ulysses.

07:44.464 --> 07:47.684
Your nephew and Mr. Forbes are

07:47.801 --> 07:48.971
waiting for you downstairs.

07:49.094 --> 07:50.644
Ah, indeed.

07:56.059 --> 07:57.769
I’ll leave ye to it, then.

08:03.316 --> 08:07.646
Do ye really think I canna feel
the look ye were giving
that poor man?

08:07.737 --> 08:09.317
[ somber string music ]

08:09.447 --> 08:12.277
I only want you to be happy.

08:12.367 --> 08:14.827
Happiness doesna come into it.

08:14.911 --> 08:17.581
In time,
Mr. Innes may afford me

08:17.664 --> 08:21.044
a wee bit of...peace.

08:21.167 --> 08:24.247
♪

08:41.312 --> 08:43.902
My apologies, gentlemen.

08:44.024 --> 08:46.864
Hmm.
No need to apologize, Auntie.

08:46.943 --> 08:49.863
We’ve come to River Run
for celebrations in yer honor.

08:49.988 --> 08:51.908
Take as long as ye please.

08:52.032 --> 08:53.952
[ chuckles ]
Well, thank ye...

08:54.034 --> 08:56.084
[ speaking Gaelic ]

08:56.202 --> 08:59.332
How generous you are,
Mistress Cameron.

08:59.414 --> 09:03.214
I’m sure Brianna must be
sensible of the kind attention

09:03.293 --> 09:05.383
you’ve bestowed
upon her son.

09:08.006 --> 09:12.126
But, uh, you’re sure
Mr. Innes understands
what this means?

09:12.218 --> 09:15.218
Mr. Innes has graciously agreed

09:15.305 --> 09:17.225
to allow me to serve
as guardian of River Run

09:17.307 --> 09:19.927
until Jeremiah comes of age.

09:20.060 --> 09:22.940
We have no children, after all.

09:24.647 --> 09:26.227
[ sighs ]

09:26.357 --> 09:28.067
Shall we begin?

09:28.151 --> 09:30.991
[ poignant music ]

09:31.071 --> 09:34.201
♪

09:35.909 --> 09:38.329
[ breathes deeply ]

09:38.411 --> 09:41.411
[ quill scratching ]

09:41.498 --> 09:44.418
♪

09:46.419 --> 09:48.749
And the colonel as witness.

09:48.880 --> 09:51.760
♪

09:56.763 --> 09:59.563
[ quill scratching ]

09:59.641 --> 10:02.601
♪

10:08.066 --> 10:09.396
There ye have it.

10:11.444 --> 10:13.074
River Run has a new master.

10:13.154 --> 10:16.284
♪

10:17.826 --> 10:21.826
And in his absence,
I should attend to my guests.

10:21.955 --> 10:22.965
You’ll excuse me.

10:24.040 --> 10:25.460
Mistress.

10:25.542 --> 10:28.422
♪

10:34.634 --> 10:36.264
‐ [ crying ]
‐ ROGER: Come, little laddie.

10:36.344 --> 10:37.644
Just a wee sniffle.

10:37.720 --> 10:39.310
It’s not so bad.

10:39.389 --> 10:41.469
‐ [ crying continues ]
‐ Ugh.

10:41.558 --> 10:44.098
What I wouldn’t give
for a box of tissues.

10:44.185 --> 10:46.145
Yeah, or some baby aspirin.

10:46.229 --> 10:48.519
‐ Mm.
‐ Here.

10:48.648 --> 10:50.018
Though I s’pose it wouldn’t
make much difference.

10:51.526 --> 10:53.146
How is it that 200 years
from now,

10:53.236 --> 10:54.356
we have a man on the moon

10:54.487 --> 10:57.697
but still no cure
for the bloody common cold?

10:57.824 --> 10:59.334
You could have gone
to the wedding, you know.

10:59.450 --> 11:01.990
I can handle a kid with a cold.

11:02.078 --> 11:06.078
I know,
but I wanted to help.

11:06.166 --> 11:09.496
[ Jemmy whimpering ]

11:09.586 --> 11:12.666
Jocasta insulted you
at our wedding.

11:12.797 --> 11:15.547
So you thought you’d insult her
by not going to hers.

11:16.676 --> 11:18.466
Well, two birds
with one stone.

11:21.097 --> 11:22.557
[ kitten meows ]

11:25.018 --> 11:28.558
‐ [ kitten meows ]
‐ Mm, Adso has
brought us a gift.

11:30.690 --> 11:31.980
What’s this?

11:32.066 --> 11:34.856
[ dramatic music ]

11:34.986 --> 11:37.856
♪

11:39.032 --> 11:42.332
[ clattering ]

11:42.410 --> 11:44.500
I don’t think that’s a gift
from Adso.

11:44.579 --> 11:47.499
♪

11:51.544 --> 11:54.174
And I hope it’s not a gift
from the gods.

11:54.255 --> 11:56.965
♪

11:57.050 --> 11:59.720
[ regal string music playing ]

11:59.844 --> 12:02.814
♪

12:04.515 --> 12:07.515
[ indistinct chatter ]

12:43.263 --> 12:46.773
It should be Murtagh
at Jocasta’s side.

12:48.476 --> 12:50.306
Instead, here I am,

12:50.436 --> 12:53.396
rubbing shoulders
wi’ the very devils
who’d see him dead.

12:55.525 --> 12:57.745
You can’t be so hard
on yourself.

13:00.113 --> 13:02.283
You asked him to wait.

13:02.407 --> 13:05.277
If Murtagh isn’t here today,
then...

13:05.368 --> 13:06.868
that’s his own choice.

13:10.456 --> 13:11.956
Come on.

13:15.044 --> 13:19.134
Let’s try and enjoy the day
for Jocasta’s sake.

13:25.138 --> 13:25.968
[ upbeat string music playing ]

13:26.055 --> 13:26.965
Aye.

13:27.056 --> 13:30.016
♪

13:54.834 --> 13:57.674
[ applause ]

13:59.756 --> 14:01.466
‐ Excuse me.
‐ CLAIRE: I had no idea

14:01.549 --> 14:03.379
you were such a good dancer.

14:03.509 --> 14:05.389
Well, to tell the truth,
I’m not certain I am.

14:05.511 --> 14:08.511
I think I must have danced
with every girl
in the province.

14:08.598 --> 14:10.638
All of them hoping to secure
an advantageous match

14:10.725 --> 14:12.525
with Lord John Grey,
no doubt.

14:12.602 --> 14:14.852
GREY: Aye, it is
the social event of the year.

14:14.979 --> 14:17.689
I’d wager there’s not
a single young lady
in North Carolina

14:17.774 --> 14:20.324
who’d forfeit her chance
to be worshipped

14:20.401 --> 14:21.901
in Cupid’s grove tonight.

14:22.028 --> 14:25.068
Speaking of never missing
a chance to be worshipped...

14:25.198 --> 14:26.868
[ indistinct chatter ]

14:26.991 --> 14:28.201
Hmm, naturally.

14:28.326 --> 14:30.036
Oh.

14:34.832 --> 14:36.792
TRYON:
Ah, Lord John Grey,
Colonel Fraser,

14:36.876 --> 14:38.536
this is an advantageous
meeting.

14:38.669 --> 14:40.049
‐ Good day.
‐ Your Excellency.

14:40.171 --> 14:41.591
Mistress Fraser,
delighted to see you again.

14:41.714 --> 14:44.014
Your Excellency.

14:44.092 --> 14:45.222
Mistress Tryon.

14:45.301 --> 14:47.341
TRYON:
Her Excellency...

14:47.428 --> 14:48.598
if you don’t mind.

14:50.598 --> 14:51.808
My apologies.

14:51.891 --> 14:54.561
Pay him no mind,
Mistress Fraser.

14:54.644 --> 14:58.194
I usually insist upon the title
as a reminder to him.

14:59.065 --> 15:01.325
And just as he’s finally
begun introducing me this way

15:01.401 --> 15:03.361
to the good people
of North Carolina,

15:03.444 --> 15:05.494
we’re leaving for New York.

15:05.571 --> 15:06.821
Typical.

15:06.906 --> 15:07.736
New York?

15:09.283 --> 15:11.993
May I introduce the honorable
Judge Martin Atticus?

15:12.078 --> 15:14.868
Your servant, sir.

15:14.956 --> 15:17.536
ARBUCKLE:
I swear, if I had my gloves,
I would throw one down.

15:17.625 --> 15:18.665
Then we would see
who had any sense

15:18.751 --> 15:20.671
of good old‐fashioned honor.

15:21.921 --> 15:23.171
Good Lord, who is that man?

15:23.256 --> 15:25.796
Quincy Arbuckle,
Your Excellency.

15:25.925 --> 15:28.835
Always at least one
self‐righteous pillock
at a wedding.

15:28.928 --> 15:30.008
[ laughter ]

15:30.096 --> 15:31.596
I’m quite surprised
by your language,

15:31.722 --> 15:34.062
Your Honor,
but, uh, can’t say I disagree.

15:34.142 --> 15:36.482
And what’s worse is,
I’m certain I attract them.

15:36.602 --> 15:39.312
The moment anyone discovers
that I’m a judge,

15:39.439 --> 15:41.069
suddenly everyone
in the vicinity is

15:41.149 --> 15:44.779
a moral philosopher
or expert in matters of the law.

15:44.902 --> 15:46.782
Well, my most recent
legislative victory

15:46.863 --> 15:48.993
was a stroke of genius,
if I may say so.

15:49.115 --> 15:50.825
Indeed.

15:50.950 --> 15:52.910
We are fortunate to have
a governor so wise

15:52.994 --> 15:56.124
and merciful to offer pardons
to these dishonorable men.

15:56.247 --> 15:59.877
My, news does travel slow
in the backcountry.

15:59.959 --> 16:01.629
Well, you have
a fellow Scotsman,

16:01.711 --> 16:03.801
Samuel Johnston,
to thank for proposing it:

16:03.880 --> 16:07.220
an Act for Preventing
Tumultuous and Riotous Assembly,

16:07.300 --> 16:11.600
prohibiting 10 men or more
from gathering under certain
circumstances.

16:11.679 --> 16:12.719
The reasoning being
if men cannot gather,

16:12.805 --> 16:14.095
they cannot conspire.

16:14.182 --> 16:15.892
Yes, exactly.

16:15.975 --> 16:17.305
If only I’d thought to do
such a thing sooner,

16:17.393 --> 16:19.983
then, uh, Lieutenant Knox
might be with us still.

16:20.062 --> 16:22.112
MRS. TRYON:
Good heavens, Your Excellency.

16:22.190 --> 16:24.730
Am I to be forever
reminding you
of proper etiquette?

16:26.444 --> 16:28.364
Very sad indeed,
terribly so,

16:28.488 --> 16:31.158
but not an appropriate
conversation

16:31.282 --> 16:32.912
for such an auspicious day.

16:32.992 --> 16:34.742
Quite right.

16:34.827 --> 16:38.037
Come, let’s leave the men
to their morbid talk
of politics.

16:38.164 --> 16:40.174
Let’s.

16:40.249 --> 16:42.669
I hear there’s a game
of high‐stakes whist

16:42.793 --> 16:44.383
taking place later.

16:44.504 --> 16:45.754
I find it very beguiling

16:45.838 --> 16:47.758
watching men gamble away
their fortunes.

16:47.840 --> 16:49.170
[ Claire chuckles ]

16:49.300 --> 16:52.220
[ ominous music ]

16:52.345 --> 16:55.105
[ locusts fluttering ]

16:55.181 --> 16:56.681
♪

16:56.807 --> 17:00.057
[ indistinct chatter ]

17:01.187 --> 17:03.147
SINCLAIR:
The swarm is gonna be here
in a day.

17:03.231 --> 17:05.441
Aye, the crop will be crawling
with the devils

17:05.525 --> 17:07.745
if we wait any longer.

17:07.860 --> 17:09.780
We should burn
Mr. Fraser’s field
and be done with it.

17:09.862 --> 17:12.912
[ people clamoring ]

17:13.032 --> 17:15.702
ROGER:
Gentlemen, please, if I may.

17:15.826 --> 17:18.246
[ clamor continues ]

17:18.371 --> 17:20.041
Fire!

17:22.041 --> 17:23.711
That got everyone’s attention.

17:26.128 --> 17:29.168
That panic you felt
in your chest, that terror,

17:29.257 --> 17:31.877
the instinct to protect
yourselves from danger...

17:31.968 --> 17:34.088
now imagine if there
really was a fire.

17:34.220 --> 17:35.600
LINDSAY:
But we’d be rid
of the buggers.

17:35.721 --> 17:38.641
Perhaps, until more come along.

17:39.392 --> 17:41.692
But you’d be ridding yourselves
of a lot more as well.

17:42.895 --> 17:44.265
One shift of the wind

17:44.397 --> 17:46.937
and your homes could be
reduced to ashes.

17:47.066 --> 17:49.686
Are you willing to take
that chance, Mr. Lindsay?

17:51.404 --> 17:52.784
SINCLAIR:
I wish Colonel Fraser
was here.

17:52.905 --> 17:54.105
He’d have an answer for this.

17:55.575 --> 17:58.085
Colonel Fraser
is 10 days’ ride away.

17:58.160 --> 18:02.250
So what is it you propose
we do, Captain Mackenzie?

18:02.331 --> 18:05.211
[ tense music ]

18:05.293 --> 18:06.423
No answer.

18:06.544 --> 18:10.264
[ people clamoring ]

18:10.381 --> 18:13.261
♪

18:15.720 --> 18:18.470
[ stately string music
playing ]

18:18.598 --> 18:21.098
I’m not saddened
by leaving the palace
at New Bern.

18:21.225 --> 18:23.095
The building has certain
elegant amenities,

18:23.227 --> 18:25.727
but I’ve never felt
comfortable there.

18:25.813 --> 18:28.193
CLAIRE:
My God, is that Philip Wylie?

18:28.274 --> 18:29.824
You know him?

18:29.942 --> 18:32.572
It’s hard to tell
under all that powder, but yes.

18:32.653 --> 18:35.703
I‐I met him at a dinner
in Wilmington.

18:35.781 --> 18:38.701
Though...I found him rather...

18:38.784 --> 18:40.334
Persistent?

18:40.453 --> 18:41.703
I was going to say annoying.

18:41.787 --> 18:42.907
[ laughs ]

18:42.997 --> 18:44.497
Ever since he returned
from Paris,

18:44.624 --> 18:46.544
he’s become
an insufferable dandy,

18:46.626 --> 18:48.126
not to mention a rake.

18:48.252 --> 18:49.382
Mm.

18:49.462 --> 18:52.172
Rumor has it he’s in
an obscene amount of debt

18:52.298 --> 18:54.298
after losing his fortune
to gambling

18:54.425 --> 18:55.975
and in houses of ill repute.

18:56.052 --> 18:57.092
Hmm.

18:58.471 --> 19:00.311
Well, he’s coming towards us.

19:00.431 --> 19:02.641
[ birds chirping ]

19:02.767 --> 19:04.137
Towards you.

19:05.686 --> 19:08.266
But perhaps I can
distract him for you.

19:08.356 --> 19:10.816
I’m the wife of a politician,
after all.

19:10.941 --> 19:13.571
It’s a particular talent
of mine.

19:13.653 --> 19:15.203
‐ [ chuckles ]
‐ MRS. TRYON: Mr. Wylie!

19:15.321 --> 19:16.861
You should have seen the look
on Robert’s face

19:16.989 --> 19:18.989
when I told him
that there were certain times

19:19.116 --> 19:20.276
during the month from now on

19:20.368 --> 19:21.538
when he would be

19:21.661 --> 19:23.831
sleeping in the guest chamber.

19:23.954 --> 19:25.714
And he agreed to it?

19:25.831 --> 19:27.081
MRS. LAURENCE:
Well, what could he say?

19:27.166 --> 19:29.246
There it was
written in plain ink:

19:29.335 --> 19:32.425
the words of this
Rawlings physician.

19:32.505 --> 19:34.345
He was cursing the day
that women were taught to read.

19:34.423 --> 19:37.433
But don’t you think it
a little sacrilegious?

19:37.510 --> 19:39.680
A child is a divine blessing.

19:39.762 --> 19:41.512
If it’s God’s will,

19:41.639 --> 19:44.469
what sort of woman would
willingly prevent herself
from bearing one?

19:46.018 --> 19:47.848
Perhaps the sort of woman

19:47.978 --> 19:49.648
who doesn’t have
the means to provide

19:49.730 --> 19:51.900
for an infinite number
of blessings.

19:52.024 --> 19:54.944
♪

20:00.866 --> 20:02.616
If you’ll excuse me.

20:03.327 --> 20:06.157
‐ Oh! Well, Mistress Fraser.
‐ Mr. Wylie.

20:06.247 --> 20:08.537
‐ [ Claire scoffs ]
‐ Deuced clumsy of me.

20:08.624 --> 20:10.544
May I fetch you something
to restore your spirits?

20:10.626 --> 20:12.246
No, thank you.

20:13.546 --> 20:14.876
How very good to see you.

20:14.964 --> 20:18.344
I assure you, madam,
the pleasure is entirely mine.

20:18.426 --> 20:21.086
♪

20:23.889 --> 20:25.219
[ scoffs ]

20:25.349 --> 20:26.479
Um...

20:26.559 --> 20:30.189
Well, you are looking well,
sir.

20:30.271 --> 20:32.231
Fortune has smiled upon me
this year.

20:32.314 --> 20:33.734
The trade with England
has quite recovered.

20:33.858 --> 20:35.478
May the gods be thanked.

20:35.568 --> 20:38.488
And I’ve had my share of it
and more besides.

20:38.571 --> 20:43.661
May I likewise observe
how becoming you look?

20:43.743 --> 20:46.413
As always, you’re a most
welcome ornament

20:46.495 --> 20:47.745
to this humble affair.

20:47.830 --> 20:49.080
[ laughs uncomfortably ]

20:49.165 --> 20:51.545
MRS. TRYON:
Excuse me, Mr. Wylie.

20:51.625 --> 20:54.835
Mistress Fraser’s aunt
is in need of her opinion,

20:54.920 --> 20:57.420
and we simply cannot
keep a bride waiting.

20:57.548 --> 20:59.508
Mr. Wylie.

20:59.592 --> 21:03.012
♪

21:03.095 --> 21:05.555
MRS. TRYON:
Forgive my tardy
intervention, but...

21:05.639 --> 21:08.269
[ indistinct chatter ]

21:15.649 --> 21:17.359
You’re doing the best
you can.

21:17.443 --> 21:19.953
Tell that to Evan Lindsay
or Ronnie Sinclair.

21:20.070 --> 21:22.740
‐ They’re afraid.
‐ So they should be.

21:22.823 --> 21:24.453
If the locusts
swarm their farms,

21:24.533 --> 21:26.453
their families will be starved
come winter.

21:26.577 --> 21:27.867
[ sighs ]

21:27.953 --> 21:29.163
If your father were here...

21:29.288 --> 21:31.118
Hey.

21:31.207 --> 21:33.537
What would he be able to do
any differently?

21:33.626 --> 21:34.916
I wish I knew.

21:36.295 --> 21:38.085
But I’m done trying
to outthink him.

21:43.093 --> 21:45.433
[ pensive music ]

21:45.513 --> 21:48.473
Funny how certain things
stick in your brain.

21:48.599 --> 21:50.389
♪

21:50.476 --> 21:53.266
Locusts and smoke.

21:54.313 --> 21:55.193
Aye.

21:57.525 --> 21:59.695
This story my father read to me
when I was a boy,

21:59.819 --> 22:01.989
it’s just‐it’s coming back
to me now.

22:02.071 --> 22:03.991
Something about a plague
of locusts

22:04.073 --> 22:05.663
somewhere in the American West.

22:05.783 --> 22:08.793
♪

22:08.869 --> 22:10.999
I hope there’s more.

22:12.331 --> 22:15.461
They used smoke
to drive them away

22:15.543 --> 22:17.093
before they could land.

22:19.046 --> 22:20.876
You think that’d work?

22:21.006 --> 22:22.876
So many stories
are based on fact.

22:23.008 --> 22:24.838
Think of all the great writers,

22:24.927 --> 22:26.637
so much truth in fiction.

22:28.639 --> 22:29.639
It could work.

22:31.308 --> 22:33.518
We could set fires
around the fields

22:33.602 --> 22:35.062
using green wood,
and when the main swarm comes,

22:35.187 --> 22:37.687
there’ll be so much smoke,
they won’t land.

22:39.233 --> 22:41.653
I mean, we’d lose
some of the crop.

22:41.735 --> 22:42.735
There’s no helping that.

22:42.862 --> 22:44.612
But if we can ward off
the rest...

22:44.697 --> 22:46.867
That could work.

22:46.949 --> 22:48.699
It could work.

22:50.870 --> 22:53.330
We just have to create enough
smoke to cover the fields.

22:53.414 --> 22:56.004
♪

22:56.083 --> 22:57.503
JAMIE:
Hanged?

22:57.585 --> 22:59.925
I thought ye said the Riot Act
outlaws assembly.

23:00.045 --> 23:01.415
It does.

23:01.547 --> 23:03.337
It also permits me
to indict any man

23:03.424 --> 23:05.014
who was seen
at the Hillsborough Riots

23:05.092 --> 23:07.052
or any past riot.

23:07.136 --> 23:09.756
Think of it as delayed justice.

23:09.889 --> 23:11.679
I mean, these men should have
been arrested months ago.

23:13.309 --> 23:15.059
And if they refuse
to submit themselves

23:15.185 --> 23:16.435
to the king’s justice?

23:16.562 --> 23:17.772
Then I’ve given
the sheriffs leave

23:17.897 --> 23:19.227
to discipline any man
who resists.

23:19.356 --> 23:20.976
As I said to you
when you first arrived

23:21.066 --> 23:22.686
on these shores, Mr. Fraser,

23:22.776 --> 23:23.896
there is the law...

23:24.028 --> 23:25.358
And then there is
what is done.

23:27.114 --> 23:28.244
I’m glad you think so.

23:30.492 --> 23:31.582
But I’m curious.

23:33.120 --> 23:34.410
Why do this now?

23:36.373 --> 23:39.173
Your wife mentioned
you were bound for New York.

23:39.251 --> 23:41.921
Yes, I begged her
to exercise discretion

23:42.046 --> 23:45.336
until it was made certain,
but, um...

23:45.424 --> 23:47.094
been offered
the governorship there.

23:47.217 --> 23:49.587
I mean, there’s a few
minor formalities

23:49.720 --> 23:50.850
that need to be observed,

23:50.930 --> 23:52.640
but I have friends
who have assured me

23:52.765 --> 23:54.395
it’s a fait accompli.

23:54.475 --> 23:55.605
Hmm.

23:57.478 --> 24:00.518
And I take it
these "friends"

24:00.606 --> 24:03.436
ken the troubles we have
with the Regulators?

24:05.110 --> 24:08.950
You know, when I first
took office in North Carolina,

24:09.031 --> 24:11.201
my wife wept for a week.

24:12.743 --> 24:16.043
I shared many
of her reservations, and yet...

24:16.121 --> 24:18.171
I must admit I have grown
quite fond of the place.

24:19.458 --> 24:21.208
Pain me to leave it in chaos,

24:21.293 --> 24:23.593
legacy of lawlessness.

24:23.671 --> 24:27.261
Some of these men
are savage at times,

24:27.341 --> 24:30.681
but they’re not
entirely godless.

24:34.181 --> 24:36.221
A legacy of mercy would be‐‐

24:36.308 --> 24:38.808
And they shall have mercy...

24:38.894 --> 24:40.234
if they choose it.

24:41.563 --> 24:44.233
Best of both worlds:
heaven or hell.

24:44.316 --> 24:47.316
[ melancholy music ]

24:47.403 --> 24:49.323
♪

24:49.405 --> 24:51.575
ROGER:
Oh.
[ grunts ]

24:53.784 --> 24:54.994
Here’s two more.

24:55.077 --> 24:56.867
‐ Thanks.
‐ [ pots clang ]

24:56.996 --> 24:58.656
Are you filling
those pots with‐‐

24:58.789 --> 25:00.169
Shite.
Aye.

25:01.500 --> 25:03.540
I’m using it
to stave off insects.

25:04.545 --> 25:07.015
And there I was thinking
it usually attracted ’em.

25:07.089 --> 25:09.589
Oh, I’m making smudge pots.

25:09.675 --> 25:11.725
They’ve been used
for centuries.

25:11.844 --> 25:14.184
Oil and dung goes in here.

25:14.263 --> 25:16.143
We don’t have crude oil,
obviously,

25:16.223 --> 25:17.853
so we’re using goose fat.

25:17.933 --> 25:22.733
When the pot’s heated,
smoke will pour out the top

25:22.855 --> 25:24.195
like a wee chimney.

25:26.150 --> 25:27.860
If we place enough of them
out in the field,

25:27.985 --> 25:30.995
it should be enough to cover
what the green fires
can’t reach.

25:31.071 --> 25:32.861
Very impressive,
Professor MacKenzie.

25:32.990 --> 25:34.200
Aye.

25:34.283 --> 25:36.453
The only problem is,
I don’t know how

25:36.535 --> 25:37.865
we’re gonna push the smoke
from the firepits

25:37.995 --> 25:39.255
out over the field.

25:39.371 --> 25:41.371
Wind’s picking up.

25:42.458 --> 25:44.168
But who knows
what it’ll be like
by the time we’re ready?

25:49.381 --> 25:50.721
I have an idea for that.

25:51.884 --> 25:53.094
Here.
I’ll handle this.

25:53.218 --> 25:54.468
You keep shoveling your shit.

25:54.553 --> 25:55.683
[ chuckles ]

26:00.476 --> 26:03.396
[ upbeat string music playing ]

26:03.479 --> 26:05.519
♪

26:05.606 --> 26:08.526
Abigail,
have you seen my husband?

26:08.609 --> 26:10.779
No, Mistress.
Shall I look for him?

26:10.903 --> 26:12.743
No.
No, thank you.

26:12.863 --> 26:13.783
Don’t worry.

26:13.906 --> 26:16.826
♪

26:18.243 --> 26:20.253
Chantilly lace,

26:20.329 --> 26:22.619
a favorite of the mistress
of King Louis of France,

26:22.748 --> 26:24.498
Madame du Barry.

26:24.583 --> 26:27.423
My humble gift to
the soon‐to‐be Jocasta Innes.

26:28.420 --> 26:31.010
[ chuckles ]
Lovely.

26:31.090 --> 26:34.510
Pity, it would look
far lovelier on you.

26:34.593 --> 26:37.143
Oh, I’m afraid such things
are hard to come by.

26:37.262 --> 26:41.102
The excise duties
are quite inconvenient.

26:41.183 --> 26:43.733
That is, unless you know
the right people.

26:43.811 --> 26:45.601
[ both laugh ]

26:46.688 --> 26:47.858
[ chuckles ]

26:47.940 --> 26:49.270
As I was saying,

26:49.399 --> 26:51.029
fine lace
is of little use to me

26:51.110 --> 26:52.150
out in the backcountry.

26:52.277 --> 26:53.397
And I was saying,

26:53.487 --> 26:54.777
if you knew the right people,

26:54.905 --> 26:56.825
you wouldn’t be languishing
in the backcountry.

26:56.949 --> 26:59.029
You’d be enjoying
the finer things in life.

26:59.118 --> 27:00.828
I can procure you
whatever you wish,

27:00.953 --> 27:03.043
whatever your heart desires.

27:03.122 --> 27:05.172
I know an Irish
seafaring gentleman

27:05.290 --> 27:07.420
who does business
in the port of Wilmington.

27:08.961 --> 27:11.091
You mean a‐a smuggler?

27:11.171 --> 27:14.221
Why, Mistress Fraser,
you wound me.

27:14.299 --> 27:16.469
Do you take me
for a common thief?

27:16.593 --> 27:19.303
I only meant to imply
that I have certain friends

27:19.429 --> 27:22.469
who are in the business
of acquiring rare

27:22.558 --> 27:25.308
and exquisite things.

27:25.435 --> 27:27.805
[ dramatic music ]

27:27.938 --> 27:29.518
Mr. Wylie...

27:29.648 --> 27:32.648
♪

27:32.734 --> 27:35.114
I have something that may be
of interest to you.

27:35.195 --> 27:38.315
♪

27:43.704 --> 27:46.624
[ string music
playing faintly ]

27:46.707 --> 27:49.667
♪

27:56.842 --> 27:57.802
Mmm.

27:59.219 --> 28:01.179
Oh, it’s absolutely sinful.

28:01.263 --> 28:02.433
[ both chuckle ]

28:02.514 --> 28:04.314
My husband makes it.

28:04.391 --> 28:06.691
Which one is he, pray tell?

28:06.810 --> 28:09.400
Silver or gold?

28:11.356 --> 28:12.436
Silver.

28:13.525 --> 28:17.485
The gold is
from my late husband.

28:19.364 --> 28:20.704
My sympathies.

28:22.701 --> 28:25.251
Do you mean to say
that Mr. Fraser
permits you to wear

28:25.370 --> 28:27.540
another man’s token
so near his own?

28:27.623 --> 28:30.963
My husband is a very...

28:31.043 --> 28:33.043
Clearly an extraordinary man.

28:35.047 --> 28:38.047
May I ask when he died...

28:38.175 --> 28:40.725
your first husband, I mean?

28:43.096 --> 28:44.556
A lifetime ago.

28:44.681 --> 28:46.891
He must have been
quite the man to inspire

28:46.975 --> 28:49.345
such devotion
after all these years.

28:50.270 --> 28:51.900
Yes, he was.

28:51.980 --> 28:54.770
A star fixed in the firmament
of a heart forever.

28:56.985 --> 28:57.895
To love.

28:59.863 --> 29:00.823
Indeed.

29:05.744 --> 29:10.544
Mr. Wylie, I was wondering
if I might ask your advice.

29:10.624 --> 29:12.834
Certainly.
I’m at your service.

29:14.920 --> 29:16.460
On a matter of business.

29:17.631 --> 29:21.381
This man of yours,
this associate...

29:21.468 --> 29:25.808
well, if he knew of a way...

29:25.931 --> 29:30.641
to circumvent certain
financial inconveniences...

29:32.312 --> 29:35.442
Anything you want,
name it, and it’s yours.

29:36.608 --> 29:38.988
Well, I was wondering...

29:39.111 --> 29:41.401
my husband’s whisky venture,

29:41.488 --> 29:43.158
it’s barely breaking even.

29:44.616 --> 29:48.116
But a partner
with the right connections...

29:48.203 --> 29:49.623
[ sighs ]

29:49.746 --> 29:53.956
Trust me, Mr. Bonnet
is possessed of...

29:54.084 --> 29:58.804
[ exhales sharply ]
Shall we say a notoriously
unhappy temper.

29:59.715 --> 30:01.975
He doesn’t do business
with people he doesn’t know.

30:02.050 --> 30:04.300
Hmm.

30:04.386 --> 30:07.096
Thankfully, we...

30:07.180 --> 30:11.730
I would be dealing
only with you.

30:13.145 --> 30:16.655
And of course there’d be
your share of the profits.

30:17.774 --> 30:21.534
It does pain me to hear
such dull words as "profit"

30:21.653 --> 30:22.993
coming out of those
lovely lips of yours.

30:24.740 --> 30:25.910
[ exhales sharply ]

30:25.991 --> 30:29.331
Let’s not spoil
such a splendid day by...

30:29.453 --> 30:32.833
talking of such
tedious matters.

30:33.999 --> 30:37.539
You’ve shown me
your pride and joy.

30:37.669 --> 30:39.169
Now I want to show you mine.

30:39.296 --> 30:42.126
[ dramatic music ]

30:42.215 --> 30:45.005
♪

30:45.135 --> 30:47.935
[ solemn music ]

30:48.013 --> 30:50.973
♪

30:57.439 --> 31:00.479
[ wagon clattering ]

31:03.362 --> 31:04.902
JOSIAH:
Take it as far as you can.

31:05.030 --> 31:07.910
♪

31:12.204 --> 31:13.964
See that the rest
of those pots are delivered

31:14.039 --> 31:15.619
to Evan Lindsay’s field.

31:15.707 --> 31:17.037
Have your brother help too.

31:17.167 --> 31:18.837
‐ Aye, Captain.
‐ Go on.

31:18.919 --> 31:21.839
♪

31:23.882 --> 31:25.552
You know, when your father
left me in charge,

31:25.675 --> 31:27.715
I thought I might have
to mend a fence,

31:27.803 --> 31:30.563
wrangle the odd runaway cow,
but no.

31:30.639 --> 31:32.719
I get a biblical plague.

31:32.808 --> 31:35.728
♪

31:47.531 --> 31:50.331
[ string music
playing faintly ]

31:50.409 --> 31:53.039
[ birds chirping ]

31:53.120 --> 31:55.370
♪

31:55.455 --> 31:56.745
[ horse chuffs ]

31:56.873 --> 31:59.583
I’d like you to meet Lucas.

31:59.709 --> 32:01.879
‐ [ horses knickers ]
‐ [ chuckles ]

32:03.588 --> 32:05.418
Magnificent.

32:05.549 --> 32:06.929
Isn’t he?

32:07.008 --> 32:08.798
I believe he’s a descendant
of Eclipse

32:08.927 --> 32:10.597
of the Darley Arabian line.

32:10.679 --> 32:12.719
Huh.
Eclipse?

32:12.806 --> 32:15.516
One of the most famous
racehorses who’s ever lived.

32:15.600 --> 32:18.140
[ gasps ]
Aren’t you sweet?

32:18.270 --> 32:20.230
Sweet?
[ scoffs ]

32:20.313 --> 32:24.153
Strange choice for such
a magnificent creature.

32:24.276 --> 32:28.146
All right, then...
good‐natured and spirited.

32:28.280 --> 32:30.620
And above all, beautiful.

32:30.740 --> 32:34.080
[ gasps ]
What the hell are you doing?

32:34.161 --> 32:36.081
Mistress Fraser, Claire,

32:36.163 --> 32:37.713
you madden me.

32:37.789 --> 32:38.829
‐ [ Claire grunts ]
‐ [ manure squishes ]

32:38.957 --> 32:40.577
[ gasps ]

32:42.294 --> 32:44.554
You bitch!

32:44.629 --> 32:46.459
CLAIRE: Jamie, no!

32:46.548 --> 32:47.878
She plied me with drink

32:47.966 --> 32:49.466
and practically begged me
to take her where she stood.

32:49.551 --> 32:51.301
The woman’s a vile succubus!

32:51.386 --> 32:52.256
How dare you?

32:52.345 --> 32:53.925
Stop!

32:54.014 --> 32:55.264
Are you really going
to kill someone

32:55.348 --> 32:56.308
at your aunt’s wedding?

32:56.433 --> 32:57.313
[ suspenseful music ]

32:57.434 --> 32:59.854
He’s not worth it.

32:59.978 --> 33:01.148
♪

33:01.271 --> 33:04.151
[ panting ]

33:04.232 --> 33:07.152
♪

33:08.361 --> 33:09.491
I see you near my wife again...

33:09.613 --> 33:10.663
[ panting ]

33:10.739 --> 33:11.859
I will kill you.

33:12.991 --> 33:14.161
‐ You understand?
‐ [ gulps ]

33:14.242 --> 33:16.452
♪

33:16.536 --> 33:19.496
[ panting ]

33:19.581 --> 33:22.251
♪

33:22.334 --> 33:24.344
[ cane clatters ]

33:24.419 --> 33:27.339
♪

33:31.968 --> 33:34.428
‐ Claire.
‐ [ exhales sharply ]

33:34.513 --> 33:36.683
What were ye thinking,

33:36.806 --> 33:38.846
spending time alone
with a man like him?

33:41.269 --> 33:42.729
He knows Stephen Bonnet.

33:44.606 --> 33:46.646
What?
He told ye this?

33:46.733 --> 33:48.993
Well, it turns out,
it’s a very small world.

33:49.069 --> 33:52.989
That smuggler he employs
in Wilmington...

33:53.073 --> 33:55.283
Wylie’s up to his neck
in gambling debt.

33:55.367 --> 33:57.827
So I‐I thought
if I could tempt him
with a business deal,

33:57.911 --> 33:59.291
then maybe he’d set up
a meeting.

34:00.622 --> 34:02.372
I had a feeling
it was Stephen Bonnet.

34:02.499 --> 34:04.459
Turns out, I was right.

34:04.543 --> 34:06.463
Christ.

34:06.545 --> 34:08.345
Speak of the devil
and he appears.

34:08.421 --> 34:11.261
[ dramatic music ]

34:11.383 --> 34:13.093
Ye willna believe this.

34:13.218 --> 34:17.558
Lord John told me Bonnet
put a dagger to a man’s eyes
in Wilmington.

34:17.681 --> 34:19.351
Just goes to show
what kind of man Wylie is.

34:20.725 --> 34:21.725
Now I’ve thrown him
in horse shit

34:21.851 --> 34:23.561
and you’ve threatened
to kill him.

34:23.645 --> 34:25.405
How are we supposed
to get him back on side?

34:25.522 --> 34:28.572
♪

34:28.692 --> 34:30.152
Ye say the man
likes to gamble.

34:30.235 --> 34:33.155
♪

34:35.574 --> 34:38.414
[ tense music ]

34:38.535 --> 34:41.415
♪

34:52.966 --> 34:55.966
[ indistinct chatter ]

35:05.770 --> 35:09.190
[ coughing ]

35:09.274 --> 35:12.114
[ locusts buzzing ]

35:13.361 --> 35:16.201
[ Roger coughing ]

35:16.281 --> 35:18.571
[ locusts hissing ]

35:18.658 --> 35:21.788
♪

35:27.292 --> 35:29.672
Don’t stop!
Keep your fires going!

35:29.794 --> 35:32.884
♪

35:43.933 --> 35:45.233
WOMAN:
Is that good?

35:45.310 --> 35:48.230
♪

36:06.331 --> 36:08.421
[ coughs ]

36:08.500 --> 36:11.170
[ upbeat string music playing ]

36:11.252 --> 36:14.212
♪

36:17.842 --> 36:20.802
[ chuckles ]
Back so soon, Mr. Barlow?

36:20.887 --> 36:23.177
I thought you’d had enough.

36:23.306 --> 36:24.676
Oh.

36:24.808 --> 36:26.928
It’s you.

36:27.018 --> 36:29.558
If you think that’s enough
to replace my coat,

36:29.688 --> 36:31.018
you’re sorely mistaken.

36:31.147 --> 36:32.817
It was given to me
by the countess of‐‐

36:32.899 --> 36:34.069
My wife was right.

36:36.194 --> 36:39.864
I, uh, canna kill a man
at my auntie’s wedding.

36:41.533 --> 36:44.373
So...

36:44.494 --> 36:46.504
it seems we’ll have
to settle this another way.

36:49.290 --> 36:51.880
If you’re referring
to the incident in the stables,

36:52.001 --> 36:53.541
it’s as I told you.

36:53.670 --> 36:55.130
I was the perfect gentleman.

36:55.213 --> 36:56.263
Hmm.

36:57.882 --> 36:58.842
[ whispering ]
Mr. Wylie.

37:01.136 --> 37:03.546
‐ Hmm?
‐ You’re acquainted
with the governor’s wife?

37:03.680 --> 37:06.770
[ indistinct chatter ]

37:06.891 --> 37:10.391
A fine woman, but, uh,
between you and me...

37:12.897 --> 37:15.397
She’s not known
for her discretion.

37:15.483 --> 37:17.403
One word in her ear

37:17.527 --> 37:19.197
and in a fortnight,
every man, woman, and child

37:19.279 --> 37:21.949
in the Province
of North Carolina

37:22.073 --> 37:25.083
will ken what kind
of "gentleman" you are.

37:26.453 --> 37:28.123
[ scoffs ]

37:28.246 --> 37:32.826
I’ve no doubt
that Her Excellency
thinks me a rake already.

37:32.917 --> 37:34.337
[ inhales sharply ]

37:34.419 --> 37:35.919
It’ll be no news to her.

37:37.172 --> 37:40.382
I’m afraid my reputation
precedes me.

37:41.676 --> 37:44.006
But, uh...

37:44.095 --> 37:46.345
she hasn’t heard the things
I have to say about ye.

37:48.933 --> 37:50.943
We settle this now.

37:51.060 --> 37:53.020
One game of whist.

37:54.689 --> 37:56.939
You win...

37:57.025 --> 37:59.115
I’ll allow you to leave
with your honor intact.

38:01.613 --> 38:03.113
And if I lose?

38:03.198 --> 38:06.618
The stallion...Lucas.

38:10.288 --> 38:14.708
[ laughs ]

38:14.793 --> 38:18.213
Oh, you Scots are all alike,
aren’t you?

38:18.296 --> 38:22.876
You brutes place far too high
a price on things like pride.

38:22.967 --> 38:25.337
The difference between
you and me, Mr. Fraser,

38:25.470 --> 38:28.390
is, given the choice
between pride and gold...

38:28.473 --> 38:30.273
I’d take gold any day.

38:30.350 --> 38:34.650
Besides, Lucas is worth
10 times this amount.

38:34.729 --> 38:36.109
[ clicks tongue ]

38:36.189 --> 38:39.569
If you want to play
at this table, Mr. Fraser,

38:39.651 --> 38:40.901
you’re going to have
to produce

38:40.985 --> 38:43.855
something far more valuable.

38:43.988 --> 38:46.778
[ dramatic music ]

38:46.866 --> 38:48.446
♪

38:48.535 --> 38:50.045
Have you lost your mind?

38:50.995 --> 38:52.325
He saw you wearing it earlier.

38:54.666 --> 38:56.496
I dinna ken why, but he says
it’s the only thing
he’ll take for the horse.

38:56.626 --> 39:00.246
Because he saw how much
this ring means to me.

39:01.840 --> 39:03.260
Don’t you see,
I humiliated him

39:03.341 --> 39:04.801
and this is his idea
of revenge.

39:04.884 --> 39:06.764
And what if it is?

39:06.845 --> 39:08.515
If I win this game,
we get the horse.

39:08.638 --> 39:10.508
If we get the horse,

39:10.598 --> 39:13.228
we get to take revenge
on a man much worse
than Philip Wylie.

39:13.351 --> 39:15.141
No.

39:15.228 --> 39:17.518
Not this.
Not Frank’s ring.

39:20.316 --> 39:21.276
Claire.

39:24.696 --> 39:26.196
Stephen Bonnet‐‐

39:26.322 --> 39:29.532
Stephen Bonnet tried to rip
this out of my throat.

39:29.617 --> 39:32.367
‐ Or have you forgotten?
‐ That’s why I need you
to trust me.

39:33.496 --> 39:35.706
This is our chance to get
the bastard once and for all.

39:36.833 --> 39:38.383
I willna lose it, Claire.

39:39.544 --> 39:41.054
And what if you do?

39:44.007 --> 39:45.417
[ sighs ]

39:49.220 --> 39:50.600
Who are you doing this for?

39:53.975 --> 39:55.435
What do ye mean?

39:55.560 --> 39:57.400
Answer the question.

40:01.232 --> 40:04.492
For Bree...for our daughter.

40:06.029 --> 40:08.529
For her honor...

40:08.615 --> 40:10.165
or for yours?

40:11.200 --> 40:13.950
[ melancholy music ]

40:14.078 --> 40:16.998
♪

40:17.081 --> 40:18.711
If you’re going to take this...

40:21.127 --> 40:23.497
Then you might as well
take both of them.

40:23.588 --> 40:26.548
♪

40:39.729 --> 40:42.519
[ soft music ]

40:42.607 --> 40:45.567
♪

40:47.028 --> 40:48.448
[ sighs ]

40:48.571 --> 40:51.531
♪

40:51.616 --> 40:53.656
We lost some beans.

40:53.785 --> 40:55.745
The cornfield was saved.

40:55.828 --> 40:58.078
It worked.

40:58.164 --> 40:59.874
LINDSAY:
Captain MacKenzie.

40:59.958 --> 41:03.088
♪

41:04.545 --> 41:05.955
Mr. Lindsay.

41:06.047 --> 41:09.337
♪

41:09.467 --> 41:11.967
I thought this plan of yours
was one of the most foolish

41:12.053 --> 41:13.303
I’d ever heard of.

41:14.305 --> 41:15.465
I’m indebted to ye.

41:16.474 --> 41:18.644
I only lost half an acre.

41:18.726 --> 41:22.056
My family willna
go hungry this winter,
thanks to you, Captain.

41:22.146 --> 41:24.316
We all helped.

41:24.399 --> 41:27.319
♪

41:30.154 --> 41:32.824
Maybe when Da returns,
he’ll promote you to major.

41:32.907 --> 41:34.697
[ laughs ]

41:34.826 --> 41:35.826
Christ.
I hope not.

41:35.952 --> 41:38.832
♪

41:57.306 --> 41:58.846
[ knock at door ]

41:58.933 --> 42:00.183
What is it?

42:03.229 --> 42:06.859
Mistress, um,
a guest has arrived late.

42:06.941 --> 42:09.281
He, uh, has a gift for you.

42:09.360 --> 42:12.360
I’ll no’ receive any more
visitors today, Ulysses.

42:12.488 --> 42:14.908
Tell him to leave it downstairs
with the others.

42:15.033 --> 42:16.953
MURTAGH:
Well, that’s a right shame,

42:17.035 --> 42:19.545
seeing as I came all the way
here to give it to ye myself.

42:22.874 --> 42:24.294
What are ye thinking,

42:24.375 --> 42:26.455
coming here today of all days?

42:26.544 --> 42:29.134
The governor himself
is downstairs.

42:29.213 --> 42:31.843
Lucky for me, I ran
into your man outside,

42:31.924 --> 42:35.644
and, well, that was before
I could do anything rash.

42:35.720 --> 42:38.310
I, um, felt it wouldn’t do,
Mistress,

42:38.389 --> 42:40.929
to have a man shot
the night before your wedding.

42:44.270 --> 42:46.060
[ door clicks shut ]

42:46.147 --> 42:48.897
[ sentimental music ]

42:49.025 --> 42:52.155
♪

42:52.695 --> 42:55.275
Ye’re completely mad,
ye ken that?

42:55.406 --> 42:57.906
Aye, I suppose
that’s part of my charm.

42:57.992 --> 43:00.912
♪

43:06.459 --> 43:08.669
I didna want to come
empty‐handed.

43:08.753 --> 43:11.713
♪

43:30.733 --> 43:32.233
Why have ye come?

43:34.695 --> 43:35.775
[ clears throat ]

43:38.074 --> 43:39.454
To ask something of ye...

43:40.535 --> 43:43.705
Something I have
no right to ask,

43:43.788 --> 43:45.618
but I will all the same.

43:49.877 --> 43:54.467
Because I can’t face
the rest of my days if I don’t.

44:00.179 --> 44:01.309
Will ye wait for me?

44:01.389 --> 44:02.639
[ gasps ]

44:04.600 --> 44:08.650
Ye ask me now,
the day before I’m to be wed.

44:08.771 --> 44:11.821
Ye have no love
for Duncan Innes.
Any fool can see that.

44:11.941 --> 44:13.651
Well, ye might have
informed me of that
the day I told ye he proposed.

44:13.776 --> 44:14.986
Ye said not a word,

44:15.111 --> 44:17.491
only that ye wouldn’t stand
in the way of my happiness.

44:17.613 --> 44:19.573
Well, I’m standing in the way
of it now, aren’t I?

44:27.999 --> 44:29.329
[ whispering ]
Christ.

44:34.964 --> 44:36.724
I didna think you’d say yes.

44:42.680 --> 44:45.270
‐ If ye’d just listen to me‐‐
‐ To what end?

44:45.349 --> 44:46.889
Ye’re a wanted man, Murtagh.

44:47.018 --> 44:48.018
Aye, for now.

44:50.062 --> 44:52.522
But to have ye by my side
in spite of everything,

44:52.607 --> 44:54.107
in spite of all
that’s happened‐‐

44:54.192 --> 44:55.732
Is that supposed
to convince me?

44:55.860 --> 44:59.860
Is that an opinion,
a reason, a question?

44:59.989 --> 45:01.819
What are ye trying to say?

45:09.290 --> 45:11.670
I told ye once...

45:11.751 --> 45:15.091
I wanted a woman
who could hear in a man’s voice

45:15.213 --> 45:17.513
that he meant
all the right things...

45:19.425 --> 45:21.635
Even if he hadna
the right words to say.

45:30.061 --> 45:31.901
[ moans softly ]

45:36.442 --> 45:39.402
[ breathing heavily ]

45:44.283 --> 45:45.533
I’m sorry.

46:00.549 --> 46:02.339
Why in God’s name

46:02.426 --> 46:04.716
would ye choose to grow old
with a man like Innes?

46:04.804 --> 46:08.354
I’ve long since grown old,
Murtagh.

46:09.392 --> 46:12.192
Ye cannot fault me
for wanting to spend
the time I have left

46:12.270 --> 46:16.770
with a good man,
man whose only cause
will be my happiness.

46:22.363 --> 46:23.993
[ speaking Gaelic ]

46:24.115 --> 46:25.625
Do you ken what it means?

46:26.367 --> 46:28.367
[ chuckles ]

46:28.452 --> 46:31.662
I shine, not burn.

46:33.624 --> 46:37.294
My father told us that you
could place a MacKenzie

46:37.420 --> 46:40.130
in the hottest fires
of hell itself,

46:40.214 --> 46:42.134
a fire that would burn
any other man to bones,

46:42.216 --> 46:43.796
but a MacKenzie wouldna burn.

46:45.261 --> 46:47.141
No.

46:47.221 --> 46:49.561
A MacKenzie would survive.

46:51.726 --> 46:53.976
The night we lost Culloden...

46:54.103 --> 46:56.903
[ dramatic music ]

46:56.981 --> 46:59.861
Hector came running
into the house

46:59.984 --> 47:02.614
with a madness in his eyes
I’d never seen before.

47:02.695 --> 47:06.115
He told us‐‐me and my youngest
daughter, Morna...

47:07.742 --> 47:10.832
Told us to gather up
all we could carry.

47:10.953 --> 47:13.793
We were going to America,
he said, to a better world.

47:13.873 --> 47:15.503
♪

47:15.583 --> 47:17.083
So we did as he bade us.

47:18.669 --> 47:21.339
And we rode off
in the dead of the night.

47:21.422 --> 47:24.222
♪

47:24.342 --> 47:27.342
We were bound for the estates

47:27.428 --> 47:29.508
of my eldest girls,

47:29.638 --> 47:30.888
Seonag and Clementina.

47:31.015 --> 47:32.685
They had bairns of their own
by then.

47:32.767 --> 47:34.807
♪

47:34.894 --> 47:38.654
I kent well
what the redcoats would do

47:38.731 --> 47:41.191
if they reached them,
drunk as they were

47:41.275 --> 47:43.185
on the blood of Jacobites.

47:43.319 --> 47:46.409
♪

47:46.906 --> 47:48.906
What I didna ken is that...

47:49.033 --> 47:53.003
Hector had stolen
a case of gold...

47:53.079 --> 47:55.659
Stuart gold...

47:55.748 --> 47:58.168
arrived from France
too late for the battle.

47:59.919 --> 48:02.879
We’d been traveling
till near dawn

48:03.005 --> 48:06.295
when two dragoons
came upon us, and...

48:06.384 --> 48:09.514
♪

48:10.638 --> 48:14.218
[ sniffling ]

48:15.559 --> 48:17.689
She was 16, Morna.

48:17.770 --> 48:20.190
She was so beautiful.
[ inhales sharply ]

48:20.272 --> 48:23.362
♪

48:23.442 --> 48:26.572
I left her there in the mud,

48:26.695 --> 48:28.855
lying next to strangers.

48:28.948 --> 48:31.618
♪

48:31.742 --> 48:34.702
Her bones may be there still,
on the road, gone to dust

48:34.787 --> 48:38.077
while I’ve sat here
for 30 years,

48:38.165 --> 48:41.535
growing old in a palace

48:41.627 --> 48:45.587
made from the gold
that took her from me.

48:46.549 --> 48:48.049
[ whimpers ]

48:48.134 --> 48:51.094
Seonag and Clementina
perished in the fires.

48:51.220 --> 48:54.140
♪

48:54.265 --> 48:55.685
[ whimpers ]

48:57.017 --> 49:01.017
[ sobbing ]

49:01.105 --> 49:02.195
I’m so sorry.

49:02.273 --> 49:04.273
[ gasping ]

49:06.360 --> 49:07.610
[ groans ]

49:09.280 --> 49:10.660
[ sniffles ]

49:10.781 --> 49:14.121
Whenever I closed my eyes, I...

49:14.243 --> 49:16.043
I‐I saw it...

49:16.120 --> 49:18.620
♪

49:18.706 --> 49:21.786
Could h‐hear Morna
screaming for me,

49:21.876 --> 49:24.336
could smell the fires
burning to the north,

49:24.462 --> 49:26.172
calling for the last
of my children.

49:26.297 --> 49:28.757
♪

49:28.841 --> 49:32.051
And when the world
grew dim around me,

49:32.136 --> 49:33.966
I saw it even clearer.

49:35.890 --> 49:40.520
My blindness is punishment
for...leaving her,

49:40.644 --> 49:43.274
for not looking back.

49:43.355 --> 49:46.525
♪

49:46.650 --> 49:49.440
Hector believed
in the Jacobite cause,

49:49.528 --> 49:50.898
and like you,

49:50.988 --> 49:52.908
he believed
he could change the world.

49:52.990 --> 49:56.280
And I lost everything
because of it.

49:56.368 --> 49:59.328
I am not Hector.
Hmm?

49:59.413 --> 50:01.163
I willna risk yer happiness.

50:03.334 --> 50:04.674
After the war to come‐‐

50:04.752 --> 50:07.752
There’ll be another
and another,

50:07.838 --> 50:10.338
on and on until long
after we’re gone
from the world.

50:10.466 --> 50:13.386
♪

50:17.723 --> 50:19.983
You‐you once said that...

50:20.059 --> 50:23.019
you wanted a woman
who truly lived,

50:23.103 --> 50:27.113
who kent what life is,
not what she wished it to be.

50:27.191 --> 50:31.821
Well, I ken what this life is,
Murtagh.

50:33.656 --> 50:35.236
And I ken what sort of man
you are.

50:35.366 --> 50:38.236
♪

50:39.912 --> 50:41.372
What sort of man is that?

50:41.455 --> 50:44.365
♪

50:46.043 --> 50:48.093
A sort of man

50:48.212 --> 50:50.882
who will lose everything
for what he believes in.

50:50.965 --> 50:53.885
♪

50:55.970 --> 50:57.510
The sort of man I swore

50:57.596 --> 51:00.216
I would never
give my heart to again.

51:02.351 --> 51:05.401
Please...

51:05.521 --> 51:07.401
go.

51:07.523 --> 51:09.943
I must rest for tomorrow.

51:10.067 --> 51:12.937
♪

51:18.742 --> 51:20.042
[ sniffles ]

51:20.119 --> 51:22.829
♪

51:22.913 --> 51:25.293
I love ye, Jocasta MacKenzie.

51:26.917 --> 51:29.127
This world may change...

51:31.547 --> 51:33.047
But that will never change.

51:33.132 --> 51:35.722
♪

51:52.192 --> 51:55.282
I only wish I’d been
brave enough to say it sooner.

51:55.404 --> 51:58.284
♪

52:05.789 --> 52:08.879
[ sobbing ]

52:10.711 --> 52:13.841
♪

52:17.301 --> 52:20.141
[ insects chirping ]

52:26.352 --> 52:27.642
[ horse chuffs ]

52:27.770 --> 52:29.150
I hope you’re worth it.

52:30.147 --> 52:32.187
[ footsteps shuffling ]

52:34.693 --> 52:36.073
I’ve been looking for ye.

52:39.907 --> 52:41.487
‐ [ scoffs ] You’re drunk.
‐ Hmm.

52:44.745 --> 52:46.125
Had cause to celebrate.

52:52.836 --> 52:54.666
I didn’t think
there was anything else

52:54.797 --> 52:56.507
Stephen Bonnet
could take from us.

52:58.342 --> 53:01.262
But you almost let him
take those.

53:01.345 --> 53:03.185
Bonnet had nothing to do
with this.

53:04.598 --> 53:07.678
You’re condemning me
for wanting to make Wylie pay
for what he did to you.

53:07.810 --> 53:09.900
No, I’m condemning you
for letting

53:10.020 --> 53:13.150
your hatred of Bonnet and Wylie
come between us.

53:14.024 --> 53:15.734
You let him use
your Scottish pride
against you.

53:15.859 --> 53:18.359
[ scoffs ]
My pride.

53:18.487 --> 53:20.067
What about yours?

53:20.197 --> 53:23.197
Ye say and do what ye like,
no matter the consequences.

53:23.283 --> 53:25.583
You think too much
from your own time.

53:25.703 --> 53:27.123
[ scoffs ]

53:27.204 --> 53:29.874
I don’t need you to tell me
how to behave, thank you.

53:29.957 --> 53:32.207
Sometimes you need reminding.

53:37.005 --> 53:39.965
You’re a woman like no other,
Sassenach.

53:40.050 --> 53:43.140
But don’t forget...
you’re still a woman.

53:45.305 --> 53:46.765
[ grunts ]

53:46.890 --> 53:49.730
[ tense music ]

53:49.810 --> 53:52.900
♪

53:53.731 --> 53:56.071
Heh.

53:56.150 --> 53:58.900
♪

53:58.986 --> 54:01.446
[ panting ]

54:01.572 --> 54:04.492
♪

54:11.665 --> 54:14.665
[ Claire gasps ]

54:14.752 --> 54:16.592
[ passionate music ]

54:16.712 --> 54:20.132
[ both panting ]

54:20.257 --> 54:22.627
♪

54:26.472 --> 54:27.642
[ moans softly ]

54:27.765 --> 54:29.565
[ both panting ]

54:29.641 --> 54:32.231
[ whispering ]
Look. Look down.

54:32.311 --> 54:34.901
♪

54:36.857 --> 54:39.277
Watch as I take ye.

54:41.779 --> 54:43.699
Watch, damn ye.
[ grunts ]

54:43.781 --> 54:46.571
[ both moaning, panting ]

54:46.658 --> 54:49.448
♪

54:54.583 --> 54:57.093
[ both gasping ]

55:02.090 --> 55:03.380
[ grunts softly ]

55:04.802 --> 55:06.852
Ye dinna hate me
for coming after ye

55:06.970 --> 55:09.720
like a...raven beast?

55:09.807 --> 55:12.267
Hmm. No.

55:14.353 --> 55:15.943
Actually,
I quite liked that part.

55:16.021 --> 55:17.271
[ chuckles ]

55:20.651 --> 55:23.491
Though I think I have
a rather nasty bruise.

55:33.163 --> 55:35.253
Wish I had seen the look
on Wylie’s face when he lost.

55:35.332 --> 55:36.212
[ chuckles ]

55:37.626 --> 55:39.996
The man was almost in tears...

55:40.128 --> 55:42.838
till I told him
I’d trade him the beast

55:42.923 --> 55:45.843
for a whisky partnership.

55:45.926 --> 55:49.346
And an introduction
to the best smuggler
in North Carolina?

55:49.471 --> 55:50.351
Aye.

55:51.515 --> 55:53.185
Mr. Bonnet will be
personally meeting

55:53.267 --> 55:55.847
Mr. Alexander Malcolm,

55:55.978 --> 55:58.728
purveyor of the finest whisky
in the Carolinas.

55:59.857 --> 56:02.777
And I thought Mr. Malcolm’s
smuggling days were well over.

56:02.860 --> 56:04.780
Mm.
[ inhales sharply ]

56:04.862 --> 56:06.532
Believe me, so did I.

56:08.907 --> 56:10.827
[ exhales heavily ]

56:10.909 --> 56:12.079
We have him.

56:13.537 --> 56:15.707
The bastard will finally pay
for what he’s done.

56:19.960 --> 56:21.170
You were right, Claire.

56:22.379 --> 56:25.299
I’m not doing this for Bree.
I’m...

56:25.382 --> 56:27.472
I’m doing it
because I‐I want to see

56:27.551 --> 56:30.431
the monster that hurt
our daughter dead,

56:30.554 --> 56:33.434
for no other reason
but I need to see it done.

56:33.557 --> 56:35.097
Is that so wrong?

56:35.225 --> 56:38.225
[ somber music ]

56:38.312 --> 56:39.232
♪

56:39.313 --> 56:40.483
No.

56:40.564 --> 56:43.534
♪

56:44.776 --> 56:46.356
Promise me, Jamie...

56:46.445 --> 56:49.075
♪

56:49.197 --> 56:51.117
Promise me
that Stephen Bonnet

56:51.241 --> 56:53.331
will never take
another thing from us again.

56:53.410 --> 56:56.330
♪

57:10.928 --> 57:12.468
I promise.

57:12.596 --> 57:15.466
♪

57:18.727 --> 57:20.647
I promise...

57:20.771 --> 57:22.401
[ speaking Gaelic ]

57:22.481 --> 57:25.781
♪

57:26.276 --> 57:29.486
That these rings will
never leave your hands again.

57:31.114 --> 57:32.454
I swear it.

57:32.574 --> 57:35.454
♪

57:55.138 --> 57:57.718
[ both clear throats ]

58:00.811 --> 58:03.651
[ ominous music ]

58:03.730 --> 58:06.650
♪

58:09.820 --> 58:12.780
Is this what the gentlemen
of America are drinking?

58:13.657 --> 58:16.407
I’m afraid they don’t serve ale
at the coffeehouse.
[ laughs ]

58:16.493 --> 58:18.043
What makes you think
I prefer ale?

58:18.161 --> 58:20.331
♪

58:20.414 --> 58:21.924
No, I‐I was just...

58:21.999 --> 58:23.879
♪

58:24.001 --> 58:24.921
Uh...

58:25.002 --> 58:27.842
♪

58:27.963 --> 58:30.553
I meant nothing by it,
Mr. Bonnet.

58:30.674 --> 58:32.844
I thank you for coming.
I know you’re a busy man.

58:32.926 --> 58:35.046
I...

58:35.178 --> 58:38.348
I’ve come from River Run

58:38.432 --> 58:40.062
and the wedding
of Jocasta Cameron.

58:40.183 --> 58:41.683
Cameron?

58:43.854 --> 58:45.654
Kin to James Fraser?

58:45.731 --> 58:50.281
The very same‐‐
Mistress Innes now, of course.

58:50.360 --> 58:53.200
Well, you must give the old bat
my heartfelt congratulations.

58:53.321 --> 58:55.281
As a matter of fact,

58:55.365 --> 59:00.115
it appears
you’re to be congratulated.

59:00.203 --> 59:04.753
Your son is now the proud owner
of River Run.

59:04.875 --> 59:07.755
♪

59:15.385 --> 59:17.175
Your Excellency.

59:17.262 --> 59:19.562
I’ve received some
rather regrettable news.

59:19.639 --> 59:21.389
It’s a shame after such
a lovely celebration,

59:21.516 --> 59:23.226
but it’s the way of the world,
unfortunately.

59:23.310 --> 59:25.060
Do you know how many Regulators
submitted themselves

59:25.145 --> 59:26.905
to the mercy of the courts?

59:27.022 --> 59:30.192
Not one.
Not one man.

59:30.275 --> 59:32.145
I had hoped
it wouldn’t come to this,

59:32.235 --> 59:33.815
but it seems we’re gonna have
our war after all.

59:33.904 --> 59:35.994
I’ve arranged
for a convoy of munitions

59:36.073 --> 59:37.493
to be delivered
to General Waddell.

59:37.574 --> 59:39.244
As soon as he is
in receipt of those,

59:39.326 --> 59:40.616
he will meet with me
in Hillsborough.

59:40.744 --> 59:41.914
You’re to gather your men
and then find us there

59:42.037 --> 59:43.037
within the fortnight.

59:43.121 --> 59:44.161
Oh, and you’re free to enjoy

59:44.247 --> 59:45.787
this evening’s festivities.

59:45.916 --> 59:47.786
[ dramatic music ]

59:47.918 --> 59:49.418
Don’t worry, Colonel.

59:49.503 --> 59:50.883
It should all be
a very quick fight.

59:50.962 --> 59:52.672
♪

59:52.756 --> 59:57.506
Aye, and the Regulators
are disorganized...

59:57.594 --> 59:59.474
no way prepared for war
against the Crown.
